botMessages.message: In order to guarantee that 401(k) plans are used for retirement, the IRS imposes age limits on specific accounts.
Since you are under 59 ½ years of age, the option to withdrawal money from your account is if you hold a rollover balance in your current plan.

First, confirm hardship withdrawals are available in your plan.​
1. From the main navigation on the left side, click “Overview”. ​
2. Scroll down to Important Information.
3. Look under Distributions to see if your plan allows for hardship withdrawals.

If you qualify to make hardship withdrawal, from the main navigation on the left, click “Withdrawals/Rollover Out” to start the process.​
Visit https://tinyurl.com/yyra3f5r for more information on withdrawals and rollovers.
Did that answer your question?

botDialogs.label: Does the plan allow for loans?

botMessages.message: The maximum loan amount available to borrow is the lesser of $50,000 (minus the highest outstanding loan balance in the last 12 months) or 50% of your vested account balance.
For more information about the loan process: https://www.myubiquity.com/whitepaper/loan-faq/.​
Did that answer your question?
Once a loan is submitted and approved by the plan sponsor, it can take up to 10-15 business days for you to receive your loan.​
Did that answer your question?

Personal loans are required to be paid off in full within 5 years of taking the loan. Residential loans allow up to 30 years to be paid. For more information on loans: https://www.myubiquity.com/whitepaper/loan-faq/
Did that answer your question?

1. From the main navigation on the left, click “Loans”. ​
2. Scroll down to “Amortization Schedule”. ​
3. Click “Export Table” to download the amortization schedule as a CSV file.
Did that answer your question?
Are you still employed by the company that runs your 401(k) plan?

1. From the main navigation on the left, click on “Loans”.​
2. Note your payoff amount as of today’s date listed as “Payoff Amount (Today)”.​
3. Write a check payable to the employer that runs your 401(k) plan*. The employer will submit the payment to Ubiquity through the 401(k) plan**.
* If you are no longer employed, you must submit final payment within 60 days of your last date of employment.
**Ubiquity cannot accept direct loan payments.
Did that answer your question?
Yes, your loans payment schedule can be changed (I.e., re-amortized). To do so, your employer's Plan Sponsor needs to email us at support@myubiquity.com to request this action.
Please note that these requests can take up to 3-5 business days to process. Also, there is a $195 fee charged to the employee's account for re-amortization.
Did that answer your question?
If you were separated from employment you have 60 days from your date of separation to payoff your loan.​

1. From the main navigation on the left, click on “Loans”.​
2. Note your payoff amount as of today’s date listed as “Payoff Amount (Today)”.

3. Send your former employer a check for the payoff amount within 60 days from your date of separation from employment.
4. The Plan Sponsor will submit the payment to the 401(k) plan. Note: Ubiquity cannot accept direct payment of your loan.
Did that answer your question?

botDialogs.label: How much does my employer contribute?

botMessages.message:
From the main navigation on the left, Select "Manage Deferrals". ​
If Roth is listed as an option, you may elect Roth contributions by adding a deduction amount. ​
The compensation limits that apply to Roth IRA's do not apply in a 401(k).​
Did that answer your question?

Yes, if your plan allows for Roth contributions, you will have the option to choose a dollar amount or percentage to contribute for both Roth and Pre-tax. Combined contributions may not exceed $19,500 for 2021.​
Did that answer your question?

If you did not elect your contribution amount during your enrollment on the selection page or wish to change the amount, you will need to complete the rest of the enrollment and then ​
1. Select "Manage Deferrals" on the main navigation page. ​
2. If you have elected to opt out previously, first check the "I wish to participate" box and select "Save."
3. From the "Choose how much you want to save" page, you will update the "Deduction Amount" and select "Save."
Did that answer your question?
See our Roth and pre-tax contribution guide: https://www.myubiquity.com/whitepaper/pre-tax-vs-roth-contribution-guide/ ​
Did that answer your question?
You may contribute up to $19,500 for 2021, plus an additional $6,500 catch-up amount for a total contribution of $26,000. You do not need to make a special election to contribute the catch-up.
Did that answer your question?
You may contribute up to $19,500 for 2021​. There are no additional catch-up contributions for individuals under 50.
Did that answer your question?

botDialogs.label: I am under 50 years of age

botMessages.message: Form 1099-R reports the withdrawal of retirement benefits.
Did that answer your question?

Withdrawals out of your Ubiquity account:​
If you took a withdrawal, cash or rollover you should have received a 1099-R form in the mail by January 31st in the following year that the withdrawal occurred.
Loans that are current and not considered in default will not be reported and do not require a 1099-R​.
Loans that were offset at the time of your distribution and considered taxable income do require a 1099-R.

Loans that ARE NOT current due to termination of employment or missed payments, may require a 1099-R. Note, the Cares Act allowed for some loan payments to be deferred in 2020, so even if your loan is not current, a 1099-R may not be required.
Please Chat with an agent or call us at 855.401.4357, Option 2, Mon-Fri 8 am – 5 pm PST if you are unsure whether a 1099-R is required for your outstanding loan.
Did that answer your question?
We can provide you with a copy. Please email us at support@myubiquity.com or call us at 855.401.4357, Option 2, Mon-Fri 8 am – 5 pm PST for a copy of your 1099-R .

If the request is after February 15th: ​
Please allow 2-3 business days for us to provide your electronic copy of the 1099-R form.
Did that answer your question?
Interest earned on your retirement account is not taxable until you take a withdrawal.
If you have not taken a withdrawal you will not receive a tax form for the interest earned on your account each year.
Did that answer your question?
